 of Reilly & Lasseigne, Haines City, for Jack M. Watkins, Sr.
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_735_416_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_735_416_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*416
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
 Mark Carpanini, Office of Polk County Atty., Bartow, for Polk County Bd. of County Comm\rquote rs.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf30 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_opinion_1}{\*\bkmkend co_opinion_1}
{\b1 \cf30 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
Opinion
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_Ifa429c13f0de11efb5a28152d422f}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_Ifa429c13f0de11efb5a28152d422f}
\par 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
SCHEB, Acting Chief Judge.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_Ifa4d4a72f0de11efb5a28152d422f}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_Ifa4d4a72f0de11efb5a28152d422f}
\par 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Thomas J. Hirt challenges the circuit court\rquote s order dismissing his amended petition for a writ of certiorari by which he sought judicial review of a zoning decision of the Board of Polk County Commissioners. Hirt\rquote s petition alleged a lack of substantial, competent evidence to support the Board\rquote s decision. In dismissing Hirt\rquote s petition, the court suggested that injunctive relief, rather than certiorari, was the appropriate method of review. We reverse and remand for the circuit court to hear Hirt\rquote s petition on its merits.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The facts relevant to our review are undisputed. Hirt owned property adjacent to an area being developed by Jack M. Watkins, Sr. Watkins\rquote  property, a planned unit development (PUD 89\u8211\'3f25), was intended to be developed in phases. The stated purpose of PUD 89\u8211\'3f25 was to develop 258 residential homesites on 58.6 acres. Opposition over the new PUD mounted when Watkins presented his proposals to county zoning authorities. Over the objections of Hirt and other property owners in the vicinity, the Polk County Zoning Advisory Board voted to recommend approval of Watkins\rquote  plans with certain conditions. Thereafter, Hirt filed for a de novo hearing before the Board of County Commissioners, a right available under Polk County Zoning Ordinance 83\u8211\'3f2 to any landowner whose property may be substantially affected due to proximity. Basically, Hirt and the other objectors contended that Watkins\rquote  proposals did not meet the minimum requirements specified in ordinance 83\u8211\'3f2 as prerequisites for approval of a planned unit development.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
On April 17, 1990, the Board of County Commissioners conducted a de novo hearing. As required by Ordinance 83\u8211\'3f2, notice of the hearing was given to all interested parties. Witnesses were heard, an opportunity for cross-examination was afforded, exhibits were introduced, and a verbatim record of the proceedings was made. At the conclusion of the hearing, the Board voted to accept the Advisory Board\rquote s recommendation and approved Watkins\rquote  proposals.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Hirt then timely filed his petition for certiorari in the circuit court, alleging a lack of substantial, competent evidence to support the Board\rquote s decision. Watkins, the developer, moved to dismiss Hirt\rquote s petition. On October 1, 1990, after extended arguments, the court dismissed Hirt\rquote s petition without prejudice for him to file for injunctive or other relief. It is this order which is now before us.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
At the outset, we point out that as the reviewing appellate court, the scope of our review is narrow. We are simply to determine if the circuit court afforded the petitioner procedural due process and applied the correct law. 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://1.next.westlaw.com/Link/RelatedInformation/Flag?documentGuid=I99a8c1590c7911d9bc18e8274af85244&transitionType=InlineKeyCiteFlags&originationContext=docHeaderFlag&Rank=0&ppcid=4d39c5b2d09a40de8aeaa94f61739dc2&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\*\shppict {\pict \pngblip \picw16 \pich16 \picwgoal255 \pichgoal255 }}}}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1982134271&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
City of Deerfield Beach v. Vaillant,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 419 So.2d 624 (Fla.1982)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. As the circuit court dismissed Hirt\rquote s petition and did not rule on its merits, it follows that if Hirt was entitled to have the Board of County Commissioners\rquote  order reviewed by way of certiorari, he was not afforded procedural due process. We think Hirt pursued the correct remedy in filing his petition for certiorari and the court erred in not hearing his petition on the merits.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F11991078711_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf41 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[1]
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Zoning decisions of county commissions and other local governmental bodies are generally classified as either legislative or quasi-judicial. Certiorari is the proper method to review the quasi-judicial actions of a Board of County Commissioners, whereas injunctive and declaratory suits are the proper way to attack a Board\rquote s legislative actions. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1964131271&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_735_829&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_735_829" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Sun Ray Homes, Inc. v. County of Dade,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 166 So.2d 827, 829 (Fla. 3d DCA 1964)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1981122153&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Town of Indialantic v. Nance,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 400 So.2d 37 (Fla. 5th DCA 1981)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
; 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
approved,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1982134270&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
419 So.2d 1041 (Fla.1982)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F21991078711_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf41 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[2]
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F31991078711_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf41 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[3]
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Courts have frequently discussed the distinction between the standards of review which furnish the guidelines to determine the validity of different types of zoning actions. It has long been established that in reviewing a legislative action, e.g., enactment of a zoning ordinance, courts must uphold a properly enacted and 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_735_417_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_735_417_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*417
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 constitutional ordinance as long as it is \u8220\'3ffairly debatable.\u8221\'3f 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://1.next.westlaw.com/Link/RelatedInformation/Flag?documentGuid=Ia31b31d40c6c11d9bc18e8274af85244&transitionType=InlineKeyCiteFlags&originationContext=docHeaderFlag&Rank=0&ppcid=4d39c5b2d09a40de8aeaa94f61739dc2&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\*\shppict {\pict \pngblip \picw16 \pich16 \picwgoal255 \pichgoal255 }}}}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1959129087&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Harrell\rquote s Candy Kitchen v. Sarasota\u8211\'3fManatee Airport Authority,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 111 So.2d 439 (Fla.1959)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. In reviewing quasi-judicial actions, however, courts are called upon to determine if the action of the local governmental body is supported by substantial, competent evidence. 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://1.next.westlaw.com/Link/RelatedInformation/Flag?documentGuid=I2c6359530c6c11d98220e6fa99ecd085&transitionType=InlineKeyCiteFlags&originationContext=docHeaderFlag&Rank=0&ppcid=4d39c5b2d09a40de8aeaa94f61739dc2&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\*\shppict {\pict \pngblip \picw16 \pich16 \picwgoal255 \pichgoal255 }}}}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1957126025&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
De Groot v. Sheffield,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 95 So.2d 912 (Fla.1957)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. This difference in the scope of review is appropriate. The judicial deference inherent in the \u8220\'3ffairly debatable\u8221\'3f standard is suitably employed to review legislative actions whereby a governmental body makes local policy decisions. Such deference, however, is unnecessary and inappropriate in reviewing issues which essentially involve a determination of whether the facts in the case being considered meet the criteria of a specific ordinance.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F41991078711_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf41 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[4]
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F51991078711_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf41 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[5]
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Whether a board\rquote s zoning decision is considered legislative or quasi-judicial appears to turn on whether the local governmental body is enacting an ordinance, in which case it is acting legislatively, or enforcing it, in which case it may be acting quasi-judicially. Thus, creating zoning districts and rezoning land are legislative actions, and as this court said in 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1987120117&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_735_249&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_735_249" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Naples Airport Auth. v. Collier Dev.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 513 So.2d 247, 249 (Fla. 2d DCA 1987)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, trial courts are not permitted to sit as \u8220\'3fsuper zoning boards\u8221\'3f and overturn a board\rquote s legislative efforts.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
However, when appellate courts have been called upon to classify governmental bodies\rquote  application of zoning ordinances, their decisions have sometimes tended to blur the distinction between legislative and quasi-judicial actions. To determine the proper classification of an action, we look to two factors: (1) the nature of the petitioner\rquote s challenge and (2) the manner in which the Board went about making its decision.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
First, as to the nature of Hirt\rquote s challenge, he acknowledges that he is 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
not
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 contesting the validity or applicability of the underlying ordinance. If he were, the proper method for review would be injunctive relief. 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See 
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://1.next.westlaw.com/Link/RelatedInformation/Flag?documentGuid=I999bf0180c7911d9bc18e8274af85244&transitionType=InlineKeyCiteFlags&originationContext=docHeaderFlag&Rank=0&ppcid=4d39c5b2d09a40de8aeaa94f61739dc2&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\*\shppict {\pict \pngblip \picw16 \pich16 \picwgoal255 \pichgoal255 }}}}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1983106030&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_735_174&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_735_174" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Florida Land Co. v. City of Winter Springs,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 427 So.2d 170, 174 (Fla.1983)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
; 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1991049120&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
City of Melbourne v. Hess Realty Corp.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 575 So.2d 774 (Fla. 5th DCA 1991)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The planned unit development concept varies from the traditional concept of zoning classifications. It permits a flexible approach to the regulation of land uses. Compliance must be measured against certain stated standards. Hirt\rquote s contention is that by not requiring compliance with certain provision of Ordinance 83\u8211\'3f2, e.g., inadequate impact statement, rights of way, and utility requirements, the Board is not properly 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
enforcing
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the ordinance\rquote s provisions with respect to PUD 89\u8211\'3f25.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Thus, Hirt\rquote s challenge is similar to that made in 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Sun Ray.
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 There, petitioners sought certiorari review of a county board\rquote s granting of a permit to erect a particular type of sign. As in the instant case, the petitioners in 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Sun Ray
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 were concerned about enforcement of an ordinance\rquote s provisions, not the ordinance\rquote s validity or applicability. The court held that since the Board was called upon to review an interpretation and application of an ordinance by a Zoning Appeals Board and the ordinance was not challenged per se, the Board\rquote s decision was \u8220\'3fclearly quasi-judicial.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Next, we consider the manner in which the Board made its decision. In 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
De Groot,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 the supreme court explained that a quasi-judicial function is characterized by a decision which is made contingent on evidence deduced at a judicial-type proceeding. 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1989006191&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Flowers Baking Co. v. City of Melbourne,
}
}
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 537 So.2d 1040 (Fla. 5th DCA)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
review denied,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1989105450&pubNum=735&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
545 So.2d 1366 (Fla.1989)
}}}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
; 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Town of Indialantic v. Nance.
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 For example, in 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
De Groot,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 a decision by a Civil Service Board regarding whether a petitioner\rquote s job should be abolished was reviewable by certiorari. The court said the Board\rquote s action was a quasi-judicial function \u8220\'3ffor the reason that it arrived at its decision after a full hearing pursuant to notice based on evidence submitted in accordance with the statute here involved.\u8221\'3f 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
De Groot
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 at 915.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In the instant case, the de novo hearing conducted by the County Commission was similar to that referenced in 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
De Groot.
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 As noted above, notice was given to all interested 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_735_418_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_735_418_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*418
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 parties, evidence was received, and a verbatim record was taken. Thus, the proceedings were clothed with all the characteristics of a quasi-judicial proceeding.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Since the Board\rquote s action was quasi-judicial, Hirt properly sought review through certiorari. At that point, the trial court should have reviewed his petition and determined if the Board provided him with due process and if its findings were supported by substantial, competent evidence. 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Deerfield Beach.
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Failure to do so was error.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Our opinion addresses only the trial court\rquote s procedural error in dismissing Hirt\rquote s petition for certiorari. Therefore, we do not express any opinion as to the merits of any of the allegations of the petition. We merely remand and direct the circuit court to reinstate Hirt\rquote s petition for certiorari and then review the Board\rquote s decision under the standards announced in 
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Deerfield.
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=h&pubNum=176284&cite=0273537801&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
RYDER
}}}
\sb200 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 and 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=h&pubNum=176284&cite=0230309001&originatingDoc=I192a63680dcf11d9821e9512eb7d7b26&refType=RQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf40 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
DANAHY
}}}
\sb200 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb600 
, JJ., concur.
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b1 \cf30 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
